## Implement now
- Create shared base types: Entity, ValueObject, Result<T,E>, DomainError.
- Create `Order` Value Objects with `create() → Result` validation.
- Create the `Order` entity/aggregate with business invariants.
- Create Domain Events for each state change.
- Define the `OrderRepository` port interface.
- Create Use Cases (one file each): CreateOrderUseCase, GetOrderUseCase, UpdateOrderUseCase, DeleteOrderUseCase.
- Write domain unit tests before touching any other layer.

## Pseudocode
```text
Entity
  id, created_at, updated_at
  equals(other) → id equality

ValueObject<T>
  immutable; private constructor
  create(raw) → Result<VO, DomainError>   // validates, then constructs
  equals(other) → value equality

Result<T, E>
  Success(value: T)
  Failure(error: E)
  map / flat_map / map_error

OrderId.create(raw) → Result<OrderId, DomainError>

Order
  fields: OrderId, ...value objects
  create(params) → validate invariants → Success(Order) | Failure(DomainError)
  behavior methods → return Result<T, DomainError>

Domain Events
  OrderCreated(id, ...fields, occurred_at)
  OrderUpdated(id, ...changed_fields, occurred_at)

OrderRepository (port — interface only, no implementation)
  find_by_id(id) → Result<Order, DomainError>
  find_all(filters) → Result<List<Order>, DomainError>
  save(entity) → Result<void, DomainError>
  delete(id) → Result<void, DomainError>

CreateOrderUseCase
  execute(params) → Result<OrderId, DomainError>
    validate = Order.create(params)
    if failure → return failure
    save via repository
    return Success(entity.id)

GetOrderUseCase
  execute(id) → Result<Order, DomainError>
    return repository.find_by_id(id)
```

## Tests required now
- `Order.create()` success + every invariant failure
- Each Value Object: valid construction + each invalid path
- Use Case happy path + failure propagation
- Domain Event fields are set correctly

